Since 1956, PTA has been involved in the development of a very successful meteorological rocket RM (Meteorological Rocket), which became the first Polish rocket to carry out scientific research.
The first type of RM-1 was completed in 1957 and the first start took place on 10 October 1958.
The 1,800-metre-long rocket was about 80 cm long and its weight was less than 5 kg.
Later an improved version of RM-1A was built and in the summer of 1959 were launched in the Bledov Desert flight test of a two-stage RM-2 rocket.
The rocket was 1.4 metres long and its weight was approximately 11.5 kg.
Another development type was already supposed to be able to do real scientific work - the RM-34 rocket was to have access to 14.5 km and its task was to monitor the high wind.
However, in 1962 another development was suspended.
The first RM rockets were followed by the Meteor-1 rocket developed between 1962 and 1965.
The rocket was conceived as two-stage, its total length was 510 cm and the starting weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types (marked Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) have been developed, which differed in the size of space for scientific instruments.
