The situation is more difficult that Europeans do not have a coherent and unified policy.
So the Germans are between two fronts.
They are expected to play an independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think they're just settling in on their role, but they're on their way to "normal" foreign policy.
To a foreign policy they have in France or in the United Kingdom.
What exactly does "normal" foreign policy mean from a German perspective?
It shows willingness to take positions in the case of national interests and positions which are independent of the positions of the US or European partners.
I think that German foreign policy is motivated by economic policy, i.e. exports and its relations with certain areas, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany's economic interests are to some extent different from those of other powers, and Germany must therefore protect its interests.
Have economic interests affected the position in the Middle East conflict and the vote in the United Nations?
First, Germany has a large residence in the Middle East, especially in the countries around the Persian Gulf.
