What is private offline is private and online
Private.
According to a dictionary published by the Royal Spanish Academy, it is something of a personal nature or a "area of private life that everyone has the right to protect against any disturbance".
What is privacy for a person under 16 years of age?
How does he apply this definition in his daily life and social networks?
Does he understand the dangers he is exposed to when he publishes things on the Internet that he would certainly not tell anyone during normal communication?
Journalists from ElPeridiodico reported five boys and girls between the ages of 10 and 15 who are frequent Internet users.
In four cases, they considered the concept of privacy to be "something entirely personal" on a personal level and as "user name and password" when it was a social network.
"My biggest secret would not be published," says ten-year-old Jorge in an effort to explain the importance of privacy in places like Facebook, Twitter, Hotmail and Windows Live Messenger, where he has had accounts for two years.
"It's a very secret secret, my mom may know about it, but not the whole world," she says.
"I put nice pictures or pictures of us playing with the FBI.
I also talk to friends there.
I wouldn't share a picture that wasn't mine, or a picture that would make someone laugh," she says.
This boy realizes that it is wrong to publish obscene photographs, photographs of naked persons or photographs of crimes, or to write humiliating or rude comments.
Jorge says he knows all 35 friends he has on FB and his nine Twitter supporters.
Most of them are related.
Among them is a mother who has the name and password of one of the accounts.
"I set up an account on Twitter so that I could express my views and write interesting contributions.
I don't know if anyone will answer me, I just put them there," he adds.
"Social networks are fun, I can talk to relatives who are far or fast to communicate with friends," she says.
Without hesitation, he says he would never accept a request from an unknown person.
He wouldn't even care if someone recommended someone unknown to him.
The case of 14 - year - old Jose is different.
This teenager owns accounts on Hotmail, Facebook, My Space and Ask networks and on the last mentioned network admits that he does not know 20 people from his list of friends.
"I'm not afraid of it because we have something in common, such as music," he says.
According to this boy, none of them pointed to anything, nor did they want an address or a phone number.
"If they insist on me or demand it from me, I will simply remove them from my account," he admits.
José applied to Ask after reading the recommendations on Twitter.
These boys are not strangers to what is now called cyberbullying.
"They blackmailed a friend on a social network.
They threatened him and asked for money.
He never found out who he was," he confirms.
According to José, the victim didn't check in.
"You just activated your private regime."
Then he explains a series of steps to set up the account safely.
Unlike Jorge, this boy would publish photos of people known in awkward or awkward situations.
"Of course I would if someone bothered me or I just wanted to.
Even though I know it's cyberbullying," he says.
Key questions
Marielos Porras, an English teacher and a graduate in the field of Education and Teaching, believes that in order for children and adolescents to get the right orientation on social networks, they need to understand that the main purpose of these networks is to inform them.
It states that: "The Internet was created as a tool for searching for information, but when social networks appeared, the rules of the game changed."
Marrielos Porrasová notes that academic worker Marc Pransky, a graduate of teaching at Yale University and author of the article Digital Natives and Digital Migrants, introduced these concepts to explain this phenomenon.
"Digital natives are children and young people who were born during this technology.
We are digital immigrants who have to teach them, and we are only learning ourselves," he says.
He explains that it is a complex topic, "because we ask them to recognize what is appropriate to spread, publish and say, and what is not, at the age when they are not yet mature".
Also in order to be smart - as far as the environment is concerned - at a time when what they desire most is to be popular, to have thousands of friends and not to think about the consequences," he adds.
According to this specialist, the most effective way to show children and adolescents what privacy is is is to ask questions that make them think.
"Telling them not to do something, it doesn't work," he adds.
Marrielos Porras also mentions some of the possibilities: Are there things you wouldn't tell a stranger, so why do you do it online?
Or, would you like it if someone published your picture the way you published your friend's?
Do you know what the others are publishing about you?
When you tag people in party photos, did you ask these people for permission?
And one more thing: Does everyone need to know all the time what you're doing?
The next point is to realize that they must behave in the environment of the Internet as well as outside it.
It's the same rules.
"A man is guided by respect, morality and other principles outside the Internet, and the same should be done on social networks," he says.
Supervision
Estuardo Guardia, a university professor, a first - grade teacher, and an education counselor, explains that it is necessary for parents of children to read the rules of social networks carefully.
"If she understands every delusion, they have a good basis to talk to the children about the consequences that the establishment of an online account can have.
