A small amount of information available to journalists was provided by press speakers from some governments who were present, but not by the Peruvian speaker.
The only document published during the negotiations was a list of participants with presidents, which caused hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who asked for more information.
Later, the Peruvian Presidential Office sent an e-mail with a "conclusion statement" from the summit, but it is only a statement by President Humalog, not an official document that the summit concluded.
Last October, Peru hosted the third summit of South American and Arab countries (América del Sur-Países Árabes, ASPA) and, even on this occasion, the originally promised Declaration of Lima was not published, although the press was zealously required.
On the official pages of the ASPA it can be found that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities sought to ensure that all journalists were broadcast, but they totally prevented the flow of information.
The summit concluded, inter alia, with a joint commitment by Chile and Peru to the adoption of the judgment of the Hague Court of Justice, which resolves the border dispute between the two countries.
